@jacobwilliams  Well, C++ is far more flexible than fortran is, and as a result with a signifcantly more complex syntax (not sure whether the syntax thing needs to be - python is also very powerful while keeping a simple syntax - but as a matter of fact C++ syntax is complex). Fortran is easier to read (except for the horrible `%` syntax for the type variables/method access), and its simplicity also makes it easier for the compiler to handle memory allocation and array optimization - two nice characteristic to write and share scientific code. Nevertheless, the flexibility of C++ (and the type-generic classes !) makes it very cool to program fancy object-oriented code. That's probably why there are so many C++ libraries out there.

I agree with @zbeekman, keep it simple, `iso_c_binding` is the way to go as the "linkage". That is the only one I know anyway. But I am not sure whether this changes much regarding to what needs to be implemented in FoBiS.py. Even with `iso_c_binding`, the C code needs to be compiled, and as such code parsing and dependency tree building on the C/C++ side needs to be done anyway... Where it can remains KISS, is by keeping the language-specific parts distinct from each other. Not sure how it is right now, but it may actually ensure that FoBiS.py code is cleanly written and nicely modular. In my understanding, the only use of assuming `iso_c_binding` interface is to say FoBiS.py that we deal with _mixed_ language code (as soon as `use iso_c_binding`) is detected in a dependency... Apart from that, the compilation remains separate and the objects only need to be indicated in the linkage step, no?

@szaghi : if it is true that supporting C/C++ with iso_c_binding involve much C/C++ specific processing steps anyway, having a slightly broader scope may actually help to attract the attention/interest of C/C++ programmers, and to have more support on this side. So I would suggest to keep it open (to the extent it does not change much to the KISS aspect of it).

