I've written a few simple caching utilities before and run into this issue as well. I'm not sure how well it would work here but my solution has tended to be to provide an additional argument for a value that the cache implementation ignores.

In this case it could look like:

```python
def get_spot():
    try:
        return backend.get(something)
    except BackendDontGotThatYo:
        return None

spot_cache = cacheutils.LRU(max_size=20000, on_miss=get_spot, ignore=None)
```

And any Nonetypes that came back would be ignored. Of course you might want something more exotic - maybe it's advantageous to cache None because it's a legit backend value but you don't want to cache if there was no backend result at all.  Then you could do:

```python
SENTINAL = object()

def get_spot():
    try:
        return backend.get(something)
    except BackendDontGotThatYo:
        return SENTINAL

spot_cache = cacheutils.LRU(max_size=20000, on_miss=get_spot, ignore=SENTINAL)
```

This way you can differentiate between a backend returning a vaild but empty or None value and an item not existing in the backend at all. This is handy because you might want to keep attempting to get that value every time because it may show up in the backend at some point and you don't want to return a False negative result.

